{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"df9a11b4-2964-4e0f-bd79-768520245ab2","content":"Analyzing .dmp files is outside the scope of my available tools, but here's how you can do it:\n\n**Using `dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n```\n\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `pe -lines` | Print last exception with source lines |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for OOM issues) |\n| `threads` | List all managed threads |\n| `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` | Inspect specific threads |\n\n**Using Visual Studio** (Windows):\n1. **File → Open → File** → select the `.dmp`\n2. Click **\"Debug with Managed Only\"**\n3. VS will show the exception, call stack, and locals.\n\n**Using `lldb`** (Linux/macOS):\n```bash\nlldb --core your-file.dmp\nplugin load libsosplugin.so\nclrstack\npe\n```\n\nStart with `dotnet-dump analyze` + `pe -lines` — that typically surfaces the exception and faulting call stack quickly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2d429476-7484-44c3-8c09-7b7990f70295","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description specifically says:\n\n- USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps, capturing dumps, setting up dump collection\n- DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is NOT appropriate here. The user needs help with dump *analysis*, not collection.\n\nLet me provide guidance on analyzing the dump file directly.","outputTokens":439,"requestId":"DA14:22AA1:5CB5C9:694086:6A03DA18"},"id":"91ed51b0-a6de-4274-897f-ee248c5c76af","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:55:51.908Z","parentId":"1c859702-e04f-4d6e-b131-e2038ce2d132"}
